\pard\plain\sa340\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 Narrative Fallacy: arise inevitably
 from out continuous attempt to make sense of the world. We humans are constantly fooling ourselves by constructing flimsy
 accounts of the past and believing they are true.}
\par
\pard\plain\sa340\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 The core of the illusion is
 that we believe we understand the past, which implies that the future also should be knowable, but in fact we understand
 the past less than we believe we do.}
\par
\pard\plain\sa340\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 To think clearly about the
 future, we need to clean up the language that we use in labelling the beliefs we had in the past.}
\par
\pard\plain\sa340\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 Hindsight: the mind that makes
 up narratives about the past is a sense-making organ.}
\par
\pard\plain\sa340\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 A general limitation of the
 human mind is its imperfect ability to reconstruct past states of knowledge, or beliefs that have changed.}
\par
\pard\plain\sa340\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 Hindsight bias has pernicious
 effects on the evaluations of decision makers. It leads observers to assess the quality of a decision not by whetherthe
 process was sound but by whether its outcome was good or bad.}
\par
\pard\plain\sa340\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 Hindsight is especially unkind
 to decision makers who act as agents for others\'97 physicians, financial advisers, third-base coaches, CEOs, social workers,
 diplomats, politicians. We are prone to blame decision makers for good decisions that worked out badly and to give them
 too little credit for successful movesecap that appear obvious only after the fact. There is a clear outcome bias.}
\par
\pard\plain\sa340\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 \'93Actions that seemed prudent
 in foresight can look irresponsibly negligent in hindsight.\'94}
\par
\pard\plain\sa340\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 Although hindsight and the
 outcome bias generally foster risk aversion, they also bring undeserved rewards to irresponsible risk seekers, such as a
 general or an entrepreneur who took a crazy gamble and won. Leaders who have been lucky are never punished for having taken
 too much risk.}
\par
\pard\plain\sa360\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 \'93A few lucky gambles can
 crown a reckless leader with a halo of prescience and boldness.\'94}
\par
\pard\plain\sa360\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 Sense-making System 1 makes
 us see the world as more tidy, simple, predictable, and coherent than it really is. The illusion that one has understood
 the past feeds the further illusion that one can predict and control the future.}
\par
\pard\plain\sa360\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 \'93The mistake appears obvious,
 but it is just hindsight. You could not have known in advance.\'94}
\par
\pard\plain\sa360\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 System 1 is designed to jump
 to conclusions from little evidence. Because of confidence by coherence, the subjective confidence we have in our opinions
 reflects the coherence of the story that System 1 and System 2 have constructed. The amount of evidence and its quality
 do not count for much. For some of our most important beliefs we have no evidence at all, except that people we love and
 trust hold these beliefs. Considering how little we know, the confidence we have in our beliefs is preposterous\'97 and
 it is also essential.}
\par
\pard\plain\sa360\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 Subjective confidence in ajudgment
 is not a reasoned evaluation of the probability that this judgment is correct. Confidence is a feeling, which reflects the
 coherence of the information and the}
\par
\pard\plain\sa360\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 cognitive ease of processing
 it.}
\par
\pard\plain\sa360\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 The main point is not that
 people who attempt to predict the future make many errors; that goes without saying. The first lesson is that errors of
 prediction are inevitable because the world is unpredictable. The second is that high subjective confidence is not to be
 trusted as an indicator of accuracy (low confidence could be more informative).}
\par
\pard\plain\sa360\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 Optimism: Optimistic individuals
 play a disproportionate role in shaping our lives. Their decisions make a difference; they are the inventors, the entrepreneurs,
 the political and military leaders\'97not average people. They got to where they are by seeking challenges and taking risks.}
\par
\pard\plain\sa580\sl-263\slmult0\wrapdefault\s24\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\fs17\afs17\ul0
{\cs18\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 When they come together, the
 emotional, cognitive, and social factors that support exaggerated optimism are a heady brew, which sometimes leads people
 to take risks that they would avoid if they knew the odds.}
\par
